column1: Biogeography of western Mediterranean butterflies: combining turnover and nestedness components of faunal dissimilarity
Leonardo Dapporto, Simone Fattorini, Raluca Voda, Vlad Dinca and Roger Vila
Appendix S1 Presence data for butterflies in the western Mediterranean.
Because butterflies are typically good dispersers, island faunas are characterized by relatively high turnover rates. Thus faunal relationships should be investigated
using data that are as synchronous as possible. For this reason, we used only published collection data or data obtained directly during fieldwork by the authors after 1980.
The distinction between data collected before and after 1980 occurs in the recent 'Distribution atlas of butterflies in Europe' by Kudrna et al. (2011),
from which most of the non-original data have been obtained. Nomenclature follows Kudrna et al. (2011) and the Fauna Europaea project (http://www.faunaeur.org/) updated with recent revisions
(e.g. Talavera et al., 2013). Data for Maghreb mostly belong to Tennent (1996) and Tarrier & Delacre (2008).
Kudrna, O., Harpke, A., Lux, K., Pennersdorfer, J., Schweiger, O., Settele, J. & Wiemers, M. (2011) Distribution atlas of butterflies in Europe. Gesellschaft fr Schmetterlingsschutz, Halle.

Talavera, G., Lukhtanov, V.A., Pierce, N.E. & Vila, R. (2013) Establishing criteria for higher level taxonomic classification using molecular data: an example with blue butterflies (Lepidoptera, Lycaenidae). Cladistics, 29, 166192.
Tarrier, M.R. & Delacre, J. (2008) Les papillons de jour du Moroc. Biotope, Mze.
